overview: The user initiated the conversation by requesting a comprehensive fix
  for a pull request in a sleep questionnaire application, highlighting critical
  issues and failing Vercel deploys. The assistant began by thoroughly reviewing
  the PR comments, CI logs, and relevant code files to understand the scope of
  the problems. A key discovery was that initial lint errors reported by CI were
  already resolved in the local codebase, allowing the assistant to focus on the
  remaining functional and security issues. The approach involved systematically
  addressing each problem from a detailed todo list. Critical security
  vulnerabilities, such as trivially forgeable admin authentication cookies,
  were fixed by implementing a secure HMAC-based session system. Data handling
  was improved by validating pagination parameters in API routes and adding
  limits to CSV exports to prevent memory exhaustion. Several bugs related to
  PDF generation, including NaN values for sleep metrics and hardcoded user
  names, were resolved. Form input handling was enhanced by allowing optional
  number fields to be cleared to null, and the "Download PDF" button was made
  functional. Finally, robust input validation was added for time fields using
  Zod schemas. All identified issues were successfully addressed, leading to a
  more secure and stable application.
